    chronology: [
      'Hanuman menemukan Sita di Taman Ashoka Lanka dan melaporkannya kepada Rama.',
      'Rama menghimpun pasukan wanara pimpinan Sugriva dan berbaris ke pantai selatan.',
      'Vibhishana membelot dari Lanka dan bergabung dengan pihak Rama.',
      'Nala memimpin pembangunan jembatan Rama Setu menyeberangi lautan menuju Lanka.',
      'Perang besar dimulai; Kumbhakarna dibangunkan dan tewas dalam pertempuran.',
      'Indrajit melukai Rama dan Lakshmana dengan Nagapasha; Hanuman membawa Gunung Dronagiri untuk Sanjivani.',
      'Indrajit tewas di tangan Lakshmana, memancing Ravana turun sendiri ke medan perang.',
      'Rama mengalahkan dan membunuh Ravana dengan panah Brahmastra menembus jantungnya.',
      'Vibhishana dinobatkan raja Lanka; Sita menjalani Agni Pariksha dan kembali ke Ayodhya bersama Rama.',
    ],
    chronologyEn: [
      'Hanuman finds Sita in the Ashoka Grove of Lanka and reports back to Rama.',
      'Rama gathers the vanara army under Sugriva and marches to the southern shore.',
      'Vibhishana defects from Lanka and joins Rama\'s side.',
      'Nala leads the building of the Rama Setu bridge across the sea to Lanka.',
      'The great battle begins; Kumbhakarna is woken and killed in the fighting.',
      'Indrajit wounds Rama and Lakshmana with the Nagapasha; Hanuman brings Mount Dronagiri for the Sanjivani herb.',
      'Indrajit is slain by Lakshmana, prompting Ravana himself to enter the battlefield.',
      'Rama defeats and kills Ravana with the Brahmastra arrow through his heart.',
      'Vibhishana is crowned king of Lanka; Sita undergoes the Agni Pariksha and returns to Ayodhya with Rama.',
    ],
    impact: '''Perang Lanka mengakhiri kekuasaan Ravana dan mengembalikan Sita kepada Rama, menutup babak besar Ramayana dengan kemenangan dharma. Vibhishana yang adil menggantikan tirani kakaknya di Lanka, sementara Rama kembali ke Ayodhya untuk dinobatkan sebagai raja, mengawali era yang dikenang sebagai Rama Rajya, pemerintahan ideal penuh keadilan. Pengorbanan para wanara, terutama Hanuman, mengangkat mereka menjadi tokoh suci yang terus dipuja. Perang ini menjadi model abadi bagi kisah kepahlawanan India, dirayakan setiap tahun melalui festival Dussehra dan Diwali.''',
    impactEn: '''The War of Lanka ends Ravana\'s reign and restores Sita to Rama, closing the great arc of the Ramayana with the triumph of dharma. The just Vibhishana replaces his brother\'s tyranny in Lanka, while Rama returns to Ayodhya to be crowned king, beginning an era remembered as Rama Rajya, an ideal reign of justice. The sacrifices of the vanaras, especially Hanuman, elevate them into sacred figures still worshiped today. The war becomes an enduring model for India\'s heroic tradition, celebrated every year through the festivals of Dussehra and Diwali.''',
    meaning: '''Perang Lanka melambangkan kemenangan cahaya atas kegelapan, kebajikan atas keangkaramurkaan, tema yang dirayakan lewat pesta lampu Diwali. Sepuluh kepala Ravana yang terus tumbuh kembali menggambarkan betapa sulitnya menaklukkan kesombongan dan hawa nafsu tanpa kekuatan spiritual sejati. Persatuan lintas wujud, manusia, wanara, dan burung, menekankan bahwa dharma menyatukan siapa pun yang berpihak pada kebenaran. Bagi umat Hindu, kisah ini menjadi teladan kesetiaan, pengorbanan, dan kepemimpinan Rama sebagai raja ideal yang menempatkan keadilan di atas kepentingan pribadi.''',
    meaningEn: '''The War of Lanka symbolizes the victory of light over darkness, virtue over arrogance, a theme celebrated through the festival of lights, Diwali. Ravana\'s ten heads, forever regrowing, depict how difficult it is to conquer pride and desire without true spiritual strength. The alliance across forms, humans, vanaras, and birds, emphasizes that dharma unites whoever stands for what is right. For Hindus, the tale remains a model of loyalty, sacrifice, and Rama\'s leadership as the ideal king who places justice above personal interest.''',
  ),
  MythStory(
    id: 'hindu-draupadi-dice',
    mythology: 'Hindu',
    icon: '🎲',
    imageUrl: 'assets/images/Hindu/History/draupadi.webp',
    title: 'Perjudian Dadu dan Penghinaan Draupadi',
    titleEn: 'The Dice Game and the Humiliation of Draupadi',
    summary: 'Yudhishthira kehilangan segalanya dalam permainan dadu curang Shakuni, hingga Draupadi diseret ke balairung dan diselamatkan dari penghinaan oleh anugerah Krishna.',
    summaryEn: 'Yudhishthira loses everything in Shakuni\'s rigged dice game, and Draupadi is dragged into court, saved from humiliation only by Krishna\'s grace.',
    timeline: 'Mahabharata · Zaman Dvapara',
    timelineEn: 'Mahabharata · Dvapara Yuga',
    chapters: [
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Latar Belakang',
        headingEn: 'Background',
        body: '''Setelah Pandawa membangun kerajaan megah Indraprastha dengan istana Maya Sabha, ciptaan arsitek raksasa Maya yang penuh ilusi optik menakjubkan, Yudhishthira mengadakan upacara Rajasuya yang mengukuhkannya sebagai raja agung. Duryodhana, sepupu para Pandawa dari pihak Korawa, diundang menyaksikan kemegahan itu dan dilanda iri hati yang mendalam. Dalam istana ilusi tersebut, Duryodhana tertipu lantai yang tampak seperti air lalu jatuh ke kolam sungguhan, ditertawakan oleh para pelayan dan disebut-sebut ditertawakan pula oleh Draupadi, istri bersama para Pandawa. Terhina dan dibakar dendam, Duryodhana kembali ke Hastinapura dan mengadu kepada pamannya, Shakuni, seorang ahli dadu yang licik dan memendam dendam lama terhadap keluarga Kuru. Bersama-sama mereka merancang tipu muslihat: mengundang Yudhishthira ke permainan dadu untuk merampas segalanya tanpa perang.''',
        bodyEn: '''After the Pandavas built the magnificent kingdom of Indraprastha with the Maya Sabha, a palace of astonishing optical illusions created by the demon architect Maya, Yudhishthira performed the Rajasuya sacrifice that confirmed him as a supreme king. Duryodhana, the Pandavas\' cousin from the Kaurava side, was invited to witness this splendor and was consumed by deep envy. Inside the illusory palace, Duryodhana was fooled by a floor that appeared to be water and fell into an actual pool, mocked by the attendants and, by some accounts, laughed at by Draupadi, the shared wife of the Pandavas. Humiliated and burning with resentment, Duryodhana returned to Hastinapura and complained to his uncle Shakuni, a cunning master of dice who harbored a longstanding grudge against the Kuru family. Together they devised a scheme: invite Yudhishthira to a game of dice to seize everything without going to war.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Permainan Dadu Curang',
        headingEn: 'The Rigged Dice Game',
        body: '''Yudhishthira, meski dikenal bijak dan adil, memiliki satu kelemahan: kegemarannya berjudi yang sulit ditolaknya, terutama bila ditantang sebagai kehormatan seorang ksatria. Ketika undangan resmi datang dari Hastinapura atas restu Raja Dhritarashtra yang buta, Yudhishthira tak bisa menolak meski Widura memperingatkannya akan niat jahat di baliknya. Di balairung yang megah, permainan dimulai dengan Shakuni bermain mewakili Duryodhana, menggunakan dadu ajaib yang telah disihir agar selalu menuruti kehendaknya. Satu demi satu, Yudhishthira mempertaruhkan dan kehilangan hartanya, kereta kudanya, budaknya, kerajaannya, lalu saudara-saudaranya Nakula, Sahadewa, Arjuna, dan Bima, yang semuanya jatuh menjadi budak Korawa. Dalam keputusasaan dan harapan membalikkan keadaan, Yudhishthira akhirnya mempertaruhkan dirinya sendiri dan kalah pula, menjadikan seluruh Pandawa budak Duryodhana.''',
        bodyEn: '''Yudhishthira, though known as wise and just, had one weakness: an irresistible fondness for gambling, especially when challenged as a matter of a warrior\'s honor. When the formal invitation came from Hastinapura with the blessing of the blind King Dhritarashtra, Yudhishthira could not refuse, even though Vidura warned him of the evil intent behind it. In the grand assembly hall, the game began with Shakuni playing on Duryodhana\'s behalf, using enchanted dice that always obeyed his will. One by one, Yudhishthira wagered and lost his wealth, his chariots, his servants, his kingdom, and then his brothers Nakula, Sahadeva, Arjuna, and Bhima, all of whom fell into Kaurava bondage. In desperation and the vain hope of reversing his fortune, Yudhishthira finally staked himself and lost as well, making all the Pandavas slaves of Duryodhana.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Draupadi Dipertaruhkan',
        headingEn: 'Draupadi Is Staked',
        body: '''Tidak puas, Shakuni menghasut Yudhishthira untuk mempertaruhkan satu hal terakhir: Draupadi, istri bersama kelima Pandawa. Dalam kegelapan pikirannya, Yudhishthira menyetujui dan kembali kalah. Duryodhana bersorak kemenangan dan memerintahkan Widura menjemput Draupadi ke balairung sebagai budak. Widura menolak perintah keji itu, sehingga Duryodhana mengutus adiknya, Dushasana, yang menyeret Draupadi dari kediamannya meski ia sedang dalam masa haid dan hanya mengenakan sehelai kain. Di tengah perjalanan paksa itu, Draupadi berteriak mempertanyakan keabsahan taruhan tersebut di hadapan para tetua: bagaimana mungkin Yudhishthira mempertaruhkan dirinya sebagai budak sebelum mempertaruhkannya, sehingga secara hukum ia sudah bukan lagi miliknya untuk dipertaruhkan? Pertanyaan tajam itu membuat balairung terdiam, namun tak seorang pun berani menjawab atau menghentikan penghinaan yang akan segera terjadi.''',
        bodyEn: '''Not satisfied, Shakuni goaded Yudhishthira into staking one last thing: Draupadi, the shared wife of the five Pandavas. In his clouded state of mind, Yudhishthira agreed and lost once more. Duryodhana cheered his victory and ordered Vidura to bring Draupadi to the hall as a slave. Vidura refused this vile command, so Duryodhana sent his brother Dushasana instead, who dragged Draupadi from her chambers even though she was menstruating and wearing only a single cloth. During this forced procession, Draupadi cried out, questioning the validity of the wager before the assembled elders: how could Yudhishthira have staked her after he had already staked and lost himself, making him no longer legally entitled to wager her? The sharp question silenced the hall, yet no one dared answer it or halt the humiliation about to unfold.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Penghinaan di Balairung',
        headingEn: 'Humiliation in the Court',
        body: '''Draupadi diseret masuk dengan rambut terurai dan dipaksa berdiri di hadapan seluruh anggota istana, termasuk kakek agung Bhishma, guru Drona, dan ayah mertua Dhritarashtra, yang semuanya terdiam membisu meski hati mereka bergejolak menyaksikan ketidakadilan itu. Karna, sahabat Duryodhana, bahkan menghina Draupadi dengan menyebutnya wanita tak bermoral karena bersuamikan lima orang, mendorong Duryodhana memerintahkan Dushasana melucuti pakaian Draupadi di depan umum sebagai penghinaan puncak. Putus asa, Draupadi berulang kali memohon pertolongan kepada para tetua yang hadir, namun tak ada yang bergerak. Dalam keputusasaan terakhirnya, ia mengangkat kedua tangan dan berdoa dengan sepenuh hati kepada Krishna, memohon perlindungan sebagai satu-satunya harapan yang tersisa ketika Dushasana mulai menarik ujung kainnya di hadapan seluruh balairung yang membisu.''',
        bodyEn: '''Draupadi was dragged in with her hair disheveled and forced to stand before the entire court, including the venerable Bhishma, the teacher Drona, and her father-in-law Dhritarashtra, all of whom sat in silence even as their hearts recoiled at the injustice unfolding. Karna, Duryodhana\'s friend, even insulted Draupadi, calling her immoral for having five husbands, which spurred Duryodhana to order Dushasana to strip her before the assembly as the ultimate humiliation. Desperate, Draupadi repeatedly begged the elders present for help, but none moved. In her final desperation, she raised both hands and prayed with her whole heart to Krishna, seeking protection as the only hope remaining as Dushasana began pulling at the end of her garment before the silent, watching hall.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Pertolongan Krishna dan Sumpah',
        headingEn: 'Krishna\'s Intervention and the Vow',
        body: '''Menjawab doa Draupadi, Krishna secara gaib memberkatinya dengan kain yang tak pernah habis: setiap kali Dushasana menariknya, kain baru terus muncul menggantikannya, hingga ia kelelahan dan menyerah, sementara tumpukan kain memenuhi lantai balairung. Menyaksikan keajaiban itu, para hadirin mulai berbisik tentang murka para dewa. Bima, dilanda amarah yang membara, bersumpah di hadapan semua orang: ia akan meminum darah dari dada Dushasana yang berani menyentuh rambut Draupadi, dan akan meremukkan paha Duryodhana yang menghina mereka dengan memperlihatkan pahanya kepada Draupadi. Merasa cemas akan pertanda buruk, Dhritarashtra akhirnya turun tangan, menenangkan Draupadi dan menganugerahkan tiga permintaan; melalui permintaan itu Draupadi membebaskan seluruh suaminya dan mengembalikan kerajaan mereka. Namun kejadian itu tak dapat dilupakan, dan tak lama kemudian Pandawa dipaksa menjalani pengasingan tiga belas tahun akibat permainan dadu kedua.''',
        bodyEn: '''Answering Draupadi\'s prayer, Krishna miraculously blessed her with an endless garment: every time Dushasana pulled at it, new cloth appeared to replace it, until he grew exhausted and gave up, leaving a heap of fabric covering the hall\'s floor. Witnessing this miracle, the assembly began to whisper of the gods\' wrath. Bhima, consumed by blazing fury, swore before everyone: he would drink the blood from the chest of Dushasana, who had dared touch Draupadi\'s hair, and would crush the thigh of Duryodhana, who had insulted them by baring his thigh to Draupadi. Alarmed by these ill omens, Dhritarashtra finally intervened, comforting Draupadi and granting her three boons; through these she freed all her husbands and had their kingdom restored. Yet the event could not be forgotten, and soon after, the Pandavas were forced into thirteen years of exile following a second game of dice.''',
      ),
    ],
    characters: [
      'Yudhishthira, raja Pandawa yang kalah judi',
      'Duryodhana, pangeran Korawa yang iri dan dengki',
      'Shakuni, paman licik perancang dadu curang',
      'Draupadi, istri bersama para Pandawa yang dihina',
      'Dushasana, adik Duryodhana yang menyeret Draupadi',
      'Krishna, pelindung ilahi Draupadi',
      'Bima, Pandawa yang bersumpah membalas dendam',
    ],
    charactersEn: [
      'Yudhishthira, Pandava king who loses the gamble',
      'Duryodhana, envious and resentful Kaurava prince',
      'Shakuni, the cunning uncle who rigs the dice',
      'Draupadi, the Pandavas\' shared wife who is humiliated',
      'Dushasana, Duryodhana\'s brother who drags Draupadi to court',
      'Krishna, Draupadi\'s divine protector',
      'Bhima, the Pandava who vows revenge',
    ],
    chronology: [
      'Duryodhana dilanda iri setelah dipermalukan di istana ilusi Maya Sabha Indraprastha.',
      'Shakuni merancang permainan dadu curang untuk mengundang Yudhishthira ke Hastinapura.',
      'Yudhishthira mempertaruhkan dan kehilangan harta, kerajaan, lalu saudara-saudaranya satu demi satu.',
      'Yudhishthira mempertaruhkan dan kehilangan dirinya sendiri, lalu Draupadi sebagai taruhan terakhir.',
      'Dushasana menyeret Draupadi dengan rambut terurai ke balairung istana.',
      'Dushasana berusaha melucuti pakaian Draupadi sementara para tetua hanya berdiam diri.',
      'Draupadi berdoa kepada Krishna, yang secara ajaib memberinya kain yang tak pernah habis.',
      'Bima bersumpah membunuh Dushasana dan meremukkan paha Duryodhana.',
      'Dhritarashtra menganugerahkan permintaan kepada Draupadi, membebaskan para Pandawa, yang kemudian tetap dijatuhi pengasingan tiga belas tahun.',
    ],
    chronologyEn: [
      'Duryodhana grows envious after being humiliated in the illusory Maya Sabha palace of Indraprastha.',
      'Shakuni devises a rigged dice game to invite Yudhishthira to Hastinapura.',
      'Yudhishthira stakes and loses his wealth, his kingdom, and then his brothers one by one.',
      'Yudhishthira stakes and loses himself, then Draupadi as the final wager.',
      'Dushasana drags Draupadi, her hair disheveled, into the royal assembly hall.',
      'Dushasana attempts to strip Draupadi while the elders remain silent.',
      'Draupadi prays to Krishna, who miraculously grants her an endless garment.',
      'Bhima vows to kill Dushasana and crush Duryodhana\'s thigh.',
      'Dhritarashtra grants Draupadi boons, freeing the Pandavas, who are nonetheless later sentenced to thirteen years of exile.',
    ],
    impact: '''Perjudian ini menghancurkan kehormatan Pandawa dan menanamkan dendam mendalam yang tak terelakkan lagi. Sumpah Bima kelak terpenuhi dalam Perang Kurukshetra ketika ia membunuh Dushasana dan meremukkan paha Duryodhana. Draupadi bersumpah membiarkan rambutnya terurai hingga dicuci dengan darah Dushasana. Peristiwa ini juga memaksa Pandawa menjalani pengasingan tiga belas tahun sebagai syarat pengembalian kerajaan, yang kelak diingkari Korawa, menjadi alasan sah bagi perang besar yang mengakhiri dinasti Kuru.''',
    impactEn: '''The gambling match shattered the Pandavas\' honor and planted an irreversible, deep-seated hatred. Bhima\'s vow was later fulfilled during the Kurukshetra War, when he killed Dushasana and crushed Duryodhana\'s thigh. Draupadi vowed to leave her hair unbound until it was washed with Dushasana\'s blood. The episode also forced the Pandavas into thirteen years of exile as a condition for reclaiming their kingdom, a condition the Kauravas later broke, becoming the legitimate cause for the great war that would end the Kuru dynasty.''',
    meaning: '''Kisah ini menyingkap kegagalan para tetua yang memilih diam demi kesetiaan formal kepada kerajaan, meski menyaksikan ketidakadilan nyata, sebuah kritik tajam terhadap kepatuhan buta. Perlindungan ajaib Krishna terhadap Draupadi menegaskan bahwa bhakti tulus kepada Tuhan tak pernah sia-sia, bahkan di saat paling putus asa. Penghinaan terhadap Draupadi menjadi simbol universal tentang martabat perempuan yang dilanggar oleh keserakahan dan kesombongan lelaki, menjadikannya salah satu episode paling dikenang dalam Mahabharata.''',
    meaningEn: '''The episode exposes the failure of elders who chose silence out of formal loyalty to the throne despite witnessing plain injustice, a sharp critique of blind obedience. Krishna\'s miraculous protection of Draupadi affirms that sincere devotion to God is never in vain, even in the most desperate moment. Draupadi\'s humiliation stands as a universal symbol of a woman\'s dignity violated by male greed and arrogance, making it one of the most remembered episodes in the entire Mahabharata.''',
  ),
  MythStory(
    id: 'hindu-bhagavad-gita',
    mythology: 'Hindu',
    icon: '🕉️',
    imageUrl: 'assets/images/Hindu/History/bhagavad.webp',
    title: 'Krishna dan Bhagavad Gita',
    titleEn: 'Krishna and the Bhagavad Gita',
    summary: 'Di ambang Perang Kurukshetra, Arjuna dilanda putus asa hingga Krishna, kusirnya, menyingkap ajaran suci tentang dharma, kewajiban, dan jiwa yang abadi.',
    summaryEn: 'On the eve of the Kurukshetra War, Arjuna sinks into despair until Krishna, his charioteer, reveals sacred teachings on dharma, duty, and the eternal soul.',
    timeline: 'Mahabharata · Zaman Dvapara',
    timelineEn: 'Mahabharata · Dvapara Yuga',
    chapters: [
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Latar Belakang',
        headingEn: 'Background',
        body: '''Setelah segala upaya damai gagal, perang besar antara Pandawa dan Korawa tak terelakkan lagi di padang Kurukshetra. Sebelum pertempuran mulai, Arjuna, panglima terhebat Pandawa, meminta Krishna, yang telah memilih menjadi kusirnya alih-alih ikut berperang dengan pasukannya, untuk mengendarai kereta perang ke tengah dua barisan tentara yang saling berhadapan. Arjuna ingin melihat lebih dekat siapa saja yang akan ia hadapi dalam pertempuran yang akan menentukan nasib seluruh Bharatavarsha. Krishna menuruti permintaan itu dan mengarahkan kereta bernama Kapidhvaja tepat ke tengah medan laga, di antara barisan Korawa yang dipimpin Bhishma dan Drona serta barisan Pandawa yang siap dengan senjata terhunus, menciptakan momen hening menegangkan sebelum tabuh perang pertama dibunyikan.''',
        bodyEn: '''After all efforts at peace had failed, the great war between the Pandavas and Kauravas became unavoidable on the field of Kurukshetra. Before the battle began, Arjuna, the Pandavas\' greatest warrior, asked Krishna, who had chosen to serve as his charioteer rather than join the fighting with his own army, to drive the chariot into the middle of the two facing armies. Arjuna wished to see clearly who he would face in the battle that would decide the fate of all Bharatavarsha. Krishna granted the request and steered the chariot, named Kapidhvaja, straight into the center of the battlefield, between the Kaurava ranks led by Bhishma and Drona and the Pandava ranks standing ready with weapons drawn, creating a tense, silent moment before the first war drums sounded.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Keputusasaan Arjuna',
        headingEn: 'Arjuna\'s Despair',
        body: '''Berdiri di tengah medan perang, Arjuna memandang berkeliling dan melihat kakek, guru, paman, sepupu, dan sahabat lama berdiri di kedua sisi, siap saling membunuh demi tahta. Tubuhnya gemetar, mulutnya kering, dan busur Gandiva miliknya terlepas dari genggaman. Ia berbalik kepada Krishna dengan pikiran kacau, menyatakan bahwa ia tak sanggup berperang melawan keluarganya sendiri meski demi merebut kembali kerajaan yang menjadi hak Pandawa. Arjuna mempertanyakan gunanya kemenangan yang dibeli dengan darah kerabat, bahkan menyebut lebih baik menjadi pengemis daripada memerintah kerajaan yang dibangun di atas pembantaian keluarga. Ia lalu duduk lemas di kereta, meletakkan senjatanya, dan tenggelam dalam keputusasaan mendalam, sebuah keadaan yang kelak dikenal sebagai Arjuna Vishada Yoga, yoga kesedihan Arjuna.''',
        bodyEn: '''Standing in the middle of the battlefield, Arjuna looked around and saw grandfathers, teachers, uncles, cousins, and old friends standing on both sides, ready to kill one another for the throne. His body trembled, his mouth went dry, and his bow Gandiva slipped from his grasp. He turned to Krishna in confusion, declaring that he could not bring himself to fight his own family, even to reclaim the kingdom rightfully owed to the Pandavas. Arjuna questioned the worth of a victory bought with the blood of kinsmen, even saying he would rather become a beggar than rule a kingdom built on the massacre of his own family. He then sank down in the chariot, laid aside his weapon, and fell into deep despair, a state later known as the Arjuna Vishada Yoga, the yoga of Arjuna\'s grief.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Ajaran tentang Jiwa dan Dharma',
        headingEn: 'Teaching on the Soul and Duty',
        body: '''Menanggapi keruntuhan semangat Arjuna, Krishna mulai mengajarkan kebenaran yang mendalam tentang hakikat kehidupan. Ia menjelaskan bahwa jiwa sejati, atman, tidak pernah lahir dan tidak pernah mati; senjata tak dapat melukainya, api tak dapat membakarnya, air tak dapat membasahinya. Yang mati hanyalah tubuh fana, sedangkan jiwa berpindah dari satu wujud ke wujud lain seperti seseorang mengganti pakaian usang dengan yang baru. Karena itu, kesedihan Arjuna atas kematian jasmani keluarganya sesungguhnya keliru, sebab yang abadi tak pernah benar-benar hilang. Krishna kemudian mengingatkan Arjuna akan svadharma, kewajiban khususnya sebagai seorang ksatria yang wajib menegakkan keadilan dan melindungi kebenaran melalui pertempuran, dan bahwa menghindar dari kewajiban itu demi rasa sayang pribadi justru merupakan bentuk kelemahan, bukan belas kasih sejati.''',
        bodyEn: '''Responding to Arjuna\'s collapse of spirit, Krishna began teaching a profound truth about the nature of life. He explained that the true soul, the atman, is never born and never dies; weapons cannot pierce it, fire cannot burn it, water cannot wet it. Only the mortal body dies, while the soul passes from one form to another as a person discards worn-out clothes for new ones. Therefore, Arjuna\'s grief over the physical death of his kinsmen was, in truth, misplaced, since what is eternal is never truly lost. Krishna then reminded Arjuna of his svadharma, his particular duty as a kshatriya bound to uphold justice and protect what is right through battle, and that avoiding that duty out of personal attachment was actually a form of weakness, not true compassion.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Karma Yoga dan Wujud Semesta',
        headingEn: 'Karma Yoga and the Universal Form',
        body: '''Krishna melanjutkan ajarannya dengan memperkenalkan konsep karma yoga, yaitu bertindak sesuai kewajiban tanpa terikat pada hasil, mempersembahkan setiap perbuatan kepada yang ilahi tanpa mengejar pahala atau takut kegagalan. Ia menjelaskan pula jalan bhakti yoga, pengabdian penuh cinta kepada Tuhan, dan jnana yoga, jalan pengetahuan sejati, sebagai jalan-jalan yang saling melengkapi menuju pembebasan jiwa. Untuk meyakinkan Arjuna sepenuhnya, Krishna mengabulkan permintaannya melihat wujud sejatinya dan menganugerahkan penglihatan ilahi sesaat. Di hadapan Arjuna, Krishna menampakkan Wiswarupa, wujud semesta yang menampung seluruh dewa, makhluk, masa lalu, dan masa depan dalam satu tubuh yang mengerikan sekaligus menakjubkan, dengan ribuan mulut, mata, dan lengan memenuhi cakrawala. Arjuna gemetar ketakutan sekaligus kagum menyaksikan keagungan kosmis itu, lalu memohon Krishna kembali ke wujud manusiawinya yang menenangkan.''',
        bodyEn: '''Krishna continued his teaching by introducing the concept of karma yoga, acting according to duty without attachment to results, offering every deed to the divine without chasing reward or fearing failure. He also explained the paths of bhakti yoga, loving devotion to God, and jnana yoga, the path of true knowledge, as complementary routes toward liberation of the soul. To fully convince Arjuna, Krishna granted his request to see his true form and bestowed upon him divine sight for a moment. Before Arjuna, Krishna revealed the Vishvarupa, the universal form containing all gods, all beings, all past and future within one body both terrifying and magnificent, with thousands of mouths, eyes, and arms filling the horizon. Arjuna trembled in both fear and awe witnessing this cosmic majesty, then begged Krishna to return to his calming, human form.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Penutup: Kebangkitan Arjuna',
        headingEn: 'Closing: Arjuna\'s Resolve',
        body: '''Setelah menyaksikan wujud semesta Krishna dan meresapi seluruh ajarannya tentang jiwa, dharma, dan pengabdian tanpa pamrih, kekacauan batin Arjuna sirna. Ia menyatakan keraguannya telah lenyap dan ingatannya telah pulih; ia kini siap melaksanakan kehendak Krishna dengan penuh keyakinan. Arjuna mengangkat kembali busur Gandiva-nya, duduk tegak di kereta perang, dan bersiap memasuki pertempuran dengan hati yang telah tercerahkan, bukan lagi dengan amarah atau ketakutan, melainkan dengan kesadaran akan kewajiban suci. Percakapan sakral antara Krishna dan Arjuna ini kemudian diceritakan kembali oleh Sanjaya, penasihat berkekuatan penglihatan jauh, kepada Raja Dhritarashtra yang buta di istananya, menjadikan seluruh dialog itu tercatat abadi dalam kitab Mahabharata sebagai Bhagavad Gita, nyanyian suci yang kemudian dihormati sebagai salah satu kitab filsafat terpenting dalam sejarah umat manusia.''',
        bodyEn: '''Having witnessed Krishna\'s universal form and absorbed his entire teaching on the soul, duty, and selfless devotion, Arjuna\'s inner turmoil vanished. He declared that his doubts had dissolved and his memory had been restored; he was now ready to carry out Krishna\'s will with full conviction. Arjuna took up his bow Gandiva once more, sat upright in the war chariot, and prepared to enter battle with an enlightened heart, no longer driven by rage or fear but by awareness of sacred duty. This sacred dialogue between Krishna and Arjuna was later retold by Sanjaya, an advisor gifted with far-sight, to the blind King Dhritarashtra in his palace, preserving the entire conversation forever within the Mahabharata as the Bhagavad Gita, a sacred song later honored as one of the most important philosophical texts in human history.''',
      ),
    ],
